{"/service/ndnp/mnhi/batch_mnhi_limbo_ver01/data/sn85025570/00383348407/1938022401/0078.xml":{"full_text":"SIXTY-NINTH YEAR REDWOOD FALLS, MINNESOTA, THURSDAY, FEBRUARY 24, 1938 NUMBER 35\n21 Teams in 3 Countv Tournaments\nRelease Complete\nInstitute Program\nEXPERTS ON WIDELY\nVARIED TOPICS TO\nGIVE ADDRESSES\nSuch widely diversified topics\nas fashion trends and sleeping\nsickness, garden pests and the\nfederal farm program, windbreaks\nand the business outlook, all of\ninterest to farmers or their wives,\nwill be taken up at the farmers\ninstitute to be held here Wednes\nday and Thursday, March 9 and\n10.\nThe complete program for the\ninstitute as outlined Wednesday\nat the county agent\u2019s office is as\nfollows:\nWednesday\n11 a. m. \u201cGardens and Garden\nPests'\u2019 H. L. Parten, state en\ntomologist. v\n11 a. m. \u201cThe 1938 Farm Pro\ngram\u2019\u2019 Skuli Rutford, agricul\ntural conservation specialist.\n1:15 p. m. \u201cElectrical Applian\nces For the Home\u2019\u2019 a demon\nstration by Miss Victoria Harris\nof the REA.\n1:15 p. m. \u201cWhat To Do About\nGrasshoppers\u201d H. L. Parten.\n2 p. m. \u201cPlanning Windbreaks\u201d\nParker Anderson, state fores\ntry expert.\nThursday\n11 a. m. \u201cThe Latest In Weed\nControl\u201d L. M. Stahler, United\nStates department of agriculture.\n1:15 p. m. \u201cFashion Trends For\n1938\u201d Orrine Johnson of The\nFarmer\u2019s Wife.\n1:15 p. m. \u201cSleeping Sickness In\nHorses\" Dr. Charles E. Cotton,\nstate livestock sanitary board.\n2:15 p. m. \u201cThe Farm and\nBusiness Outlook for 1938\u201d\nBerry H. Akers, editor of The\nFarmer.\nTwo classes at the same hours\nwere scheduled because one sub\nject is of interest to women, the\nother to men.\nThe institute is sponsored by\nthe Redwood Falls Civic and\nCommerce association which is\narranging for free noon lunches\nand musical entertainment.\nAn institute is also planned at\nLamberton March 7.\nBoard Wants\nSummer Play\nSupervision\nCITY, SCHOOL WOULD\nSHARE COST UNDER\nPROPOSED PLAN\nA motion recommending the\nemployment of a summer play\nground supervisor at Memorial\nfield was passed at the annual\nmeeting of the board of directors\nof the Redwood Falls Recreational\nassociation in Lauterbach\u2019s Friday\nnoon. The board suggested that\nthe school district and city each\npay half of the supervisor\u2019s sal\nary.\nReede Gray, secretary of the\norganization, indicated that the\nschool board is apparently willing\nto divide expenses on the project,\nand would employ someone well\nqualified for the work.\nAll officers of the board were\nre-elected. J. L. Parsons is presi\ndent, Rev. Geoffrey O\u2019Sullivan,\nvice-president, L. R. Ewart, trea\nsurer and Mr. Gray, secretary.\nOther members are Dr. J. Gordon\nCole, Mayor J. F: Knudson and\nRichard Cook.\nThe group discussed the Mem\norial Field stadium project now\nunderway. At present 20 men are\nemployed, excavations for foot\nings are practically complete and\nconcrete work will be started\nsoon. Within a week about 40\nmen will be employed and part of\nthese will be put to work tearing\nup the foundations of the old\nLight and Power plant for rock\nto be used in the stadium. The\nmaterial will supplement stone\nfrom the old high school building,\nApproval of R. F. Byram as fore\nman of the stadium project was\nreceived from WPA authorities\nthis week.\nProminent Missions\nWorker Visits Here\nRev. Kenneth W. Moore, whose\nwife is the former Ella Crimmins,\nis visiting her parents, Mr. and\nMrs. D. L. Crimmins, here today.\nRev. Moore is United States\ntreasurer of foreign missions in\nthe Presbyterian church and has\nbeen attending meetings of mis\nsions groups in Minneapolis and\nSt. Paul this week. His office is\nin New York city.\nCorn Loan Deadline\nThe Redwood county com loan\noffice reminds farmers that all\nloans must be completed and re\ncorded with the register of deeds\nby March 31. They state that\nsometimes as much as three\nweeks is required to obtain lien\nwaivers on corn and ask that bor\nrowers co-operate with them in\nmaking the deadline.\nTHE REDWOOD GAZETTE 3\nWOOD LAKE STORE\nBURNED MONDAY\nWood Lake\u2014The Clover Farm\nstore was burned and merchan\ndise valued at about $5,000 des\ntroyed Monday in one of the worst\nfires in the history of Wood Lake.\nThe stock was owned by L. L.\nEldred and the building by the\nJulius Fillbrandt estate.\nOf unknown origin, the fire was\ndiscovered early Monday morning\nby Julius Trojohn who had been\nsorting the mail. Seeing what he\nthought was steam issing from\nthe roof, he kicked open a rear\ndoor, to have a swirl of heat,\nsmoke and fire roll out.\nThe fire department was called,\nremaining at the scene for hours.\nHundreds of pounds, of meat\nwhich Mr. Eldred was smoking\nfor farmers was destroyed in the\nfire.\nHe was in Young Ameriea visit\ning relatives at the time.\nUnemployed\nGet Checks\nFIRST BENEFITS FROM\nNEW LAW RECEIVED\nLATE LAST WEEK\nFirst state unemployment com\npensation checks to be received in\nthe Redwood Falls community\narrived late last week. J. W.\nLauteibach of the Minnesota Em\nployment Service said officials are\nnot allowed to give out informa\ntion cn the amounts received or\nrecipients.\nThe number of weeks of bene\nt3 to which workers now receiv\ning checks under the compensa\nicn law are entitled depends upon\ntheir earnings during the first\nn.ne months of 1937. Earnings\nduring October, November and\nDecember cannot be counted in\ndetei mining the duration of bene\nfit claims filed before April 1 of\nthis year.\nBeginning this week the em\nployment office will be open dur\ning the noon hour. If will be\nclosed all day Saturday, having\nbeen kept open on Washington\u2019s\nbirthday.\nAlbert Kayser sustained a frac-\u00bb\nture of the left ankle in an acci\ndent at the WNAX station Friday\nf ter noon.\nMilroy Pioneers Mark Member\u2019s Birthday\nThis snapshot was taken at the\nbirthday party of J. W. Dysart of\nMilroy who was 81 February 16.\nGuests are, from left to right, R.\nF. Edwards, P. H. Kelly, 64; C.\nG. Seeman, 67; Mr. Dysart, J. C.\nLarson, 65; Iver Heier, 64 and H.\nLookin Lovely Offers Good Roles\nFor Juniors; Will be Qiven Friday\nFirst Candidate\nJoe Mahal of Vail township fil\ned for the office of sheriff Wed\nnesday afternoon. He is the first\nman to enter the county race.\nMahal polled 774 votes to run\nthird in the 1934 primary election\nin a field of nine candidates for\nthe office.\nMore Relief Work\nOffered in County\nSeveral WPA workers will be\nadded to Redwood county roles\nby March 1, following a state\nplan to offer jobs to all certified\nrelief persons suitable for avail\nable work. At present there are\nabout 80 men employed in the\ncounty on the Ramsey park, Mem\norial stadium and Sanborn bridge\nprojects.\nGame League\nWill Take Up,\nVital Topics\nTHREE POND UNIT FOR\nFISH PROPAGATION\nINCLUDED IN PLANS\nThe annual meeting of the Red\nwood County Game Protective\nleague will be held Friday at 7: 30\np. m. in the Redwood Falls city\nhall.\nThere will be election of officers\nand discussion of such matters as\nparticipation in a statewide fox\nand crow hunt, procuring a three\npond unit for fish propagation in\nthis section and game preserves.\n\u201cThese and other important\nmatters to come up are of vital\ninterest to the sportsmen of this\ncommunity and it is hoped that\nnot only present game league\nmembers, but all parties interest\ned in the sport of hunting and\nfishing will be at-this meeting and\nlend their support to the matters\nat hand,\u201d the announcement of the\nmeeting stated.\n\u201cIf you hunt and fish you owe\nit to yourself and future genera\ntions to replenish the game and\nfish you enjoy taking now. Don\u2019t\nbe a slacker, but show the sports\nmanship that\u2019s in you by attend\nng this meeting.\n\u201cYou should be a member if\nyou are not now and surely for\n*he fee of 50 cents you cannot af\nford to be without a membership\nin the Redwood County Game\nProtective league.\n\u201cMay we count on you as a\ngood sport?\u201d the appeal conclud\ned.\nTO ATTEND MEETING\nMembers of the Redwood Falls\nOdd Fellows will attend a state\nmeeting of the lodge in Willmar\nSaturday evening. George T.\nFreyer, past grand master, will\nassist in ceremonies. About 100\ncandidates will receive their de\ngrees and 5,000 persons are ex\npected to attend. R. W. Whyte,\npast grand patriarch, will be un\nable to attend because of a recent\nleg injury.\nP. Nelson, 80, all old friends who\nenjoyed supper and spent a pleas\nant evening together. G. T: Wis\ntad, T. F. Reed Sr. and Peter Scott\nwho usually attend the annual\nparty, were unable to be present.\nA more sophisticated type of\nplay than those put on in recent\nyears will be presented by a \"cast\nof 12 junior high school students\nat 8 p. m. Friday on the new high\nschool stage.\n\u201cLookin\u2019 Lovely\u201d is a three act\ncomedy portraying situations de\nveloping when an inherited an\ncestral farm is turned into a\nbeauty institute specializing in\nfacial masks and other mud treat\nments.\nAn Englishman characterized\nby Kenneth Parsons, a Jew por\ntrayed by George Steele, a negro\ncook played by Agnes Coleman\nand Ellis Lang as a sheriff are\namong the outstanding personages\nin the production.\nOther members of the cast are\nThorine Johnson as Winnie Bor\ndine who has inherited the debt\nridden farm; Norma Domfeld as\nAmarilla, the village postmistress\nand broadcaster; Mary Hoffman\nand Dean Muetzel as Clytie and\nBuddie ,Winnie\u2019s brother and sis\nter; Irene Shemon as Jennie Mat\nhews, now on the stage; Magde\nlyn Johanneck as Esther Hastings\nwho has been abroad; Norman\nOtto as Bill Baker, a promoter\nlooking for something to promote\nand Arthur Neuschwander as Jim\nDugan, his pal and fellow-pro\nmoter.\nMiss Hazel Domfeld is direct\ning the play.\nHit Snags in Hunt\nFor Station Bandit\nMonday Last Day\nTo Settle Taxes\nWithout Penalty\nMonday is the last day in\nwhich to pay your personal\nproperty taxes, County Trea\nsurer A. P. Falk reminds in\na plea not to wait uniil the\nlast minute and thereby snow\nhim and his assistant E. W.\nCurrier under a pile of\nblanks.\nTaxes are coming in fairly\nsteadily, about 2100 receipt\nblanks having been made out\nso far. That total is about 150\nless than at the same time\nlast year.\nAn eight per cent penalty\nis charged against taxes not\npaid by March 1.\nLITTLE TEN HIGH\nSCHOOLS TO GIVE\nOWN QUESTIONS\nOTHER SCHOOLS MAY\nALSO GIVE TESTS\nUSED IN LEAGUE\nHigh school students in the\nLittle Ten group will have stand\nard examinations of their own to\nreplace state exams, pupil buga\nboo for years, it was decided at a\nmeeting of superintendents of the\nconference at New Ulm Monday\nafterr.oon and evening. Seventh\nand eighth graders, however, will\ncontinue to take \u201cstates\u201d.\nSchool authorities of Redwood\nFalls, Tracy, New Ulm, Spring\nfield, Sleepy Eye, Fairmont, St.\nJames, Marshall, Hutchinson, and\nGlencoe are already at work\npreparing questions for examin\nations ,in which former stat%\nquizzers, book publishers\u2019 ques\ntions and teachers\u2019 suggestions\nwill be incorporated.\nThe tests will be standardized\nand designed to keep Little Ten\nhigh school instruction equalized.\nOther schools in this area not in\ncluded in the conference have al\nready asked for information on\nthe new move and it is expected\nthat the exams will be widely\nused in nearby institutions.\nDELUXE CLEANERS\nWILL OPEN FRIDAY\nEQUIPMENT INSTALLED\nFOR FIRM OWNED BY\nDWYER AND HAGEN\nThe De Luxe Cleaners, owned\nby Leo Dwyer and Helmuth\nHagen, will open Friday. The new\nestablishment is located under\nBen\u2019s Cafe on Washington street.\nExtensive remodeling and de\ncorating has been done in the\nshop rooms. A soft pale green\nwainscoting is set off by buff\nwoodwork and natural nu-wood\nforms the upper walls and ceil\nings which are decorated in tiled\neffect.\nIn the office there are finished\nclothing alcoves, a built-in hat\ncase and a shelf for displaying\nsamples of tailoring. The work\nroom equipment includes the lat\nest model pressing machine and\na machine for automatically iron\ning hats, heated electrically.\nSmall casement windows open\noff the work room to the cleaning\nroom in which a Band-Box unit\nis installed. Steam for the presser\ncomes from a separate boiler\nroom equipped with an oil burn\ner.\nTo the right of the office en\ntrance is a small dressing room\nfor the convenience of customers.\nREFUND OF AAA\nTAXES SOUGHT\nBetween 75 and 100 farmers at\ntended a meeting held by repre\nsentatives of the House of Gurney\nat Yankton in the American Le\ngion hall here Wednesday night.\nD. B. Gurney is conducting a\ncampaign for collection of pro\ncessing taxes paid on hogs by\nnon-signers during the AAA per\niod.\nHe asks a $2 fee for claims of\nSIOO or less, two per cent of the\ntotal claim for those from SIOO to\nS4OO and $8 for claims from S4OO\nto S9OO. The fees, he says, are\nfor the costs of preparing claims.\nNo processing taxes can be re\nfunded without an act of congress,\nwhich he states is pending.\nAt the meeting speakers present\ned analysis of hog sales to show\nthat the farmer, not the processor\nor consumer, paid the processing\ntax. That question, authorities\nsay, is open to argument.\nRecently agricultural officials\nat Washington warned fanners\nagainst paying fees for work on\nrefundment of processing\nSANBORN MAN FAILS\nTO IDENTIFY PIC\nTURES OF THUGS\nSearchers for a gunman who\nrobbed the Sanborn station oper\nator of an express shipment of\n$2,000 in currency and about $25\nin silver early Saturday morning\nstruck two snags this week.\nChester W. Schultz, telegraph\noperator at the depot for 20 years,\nwas unable to identify any pic\ntures of criminals shown him by\nexpress company detectives in\nMinneapolis Monday as those of\nan armed assailant who forced\nhim to open the station safe con\ntaining the money and then slug\nged him with his fist.\nSheriff L. J. Kise found that\nno serial numbers had been re\ncorded on the shipment, all in\nused dollar bills, which was en\nroute from the First National\nBank and Trust company in Min\nneapolis to the Wanda State bank.\nThe bills were for use by the\nWanda creamery.\nReported Theft\nSchultz called Sheriff Kise\nshortly after 3 a. m. to report the\ntheft, stating he watched the rob\nber leave the station, then heard\na car start and saw it head north\non highway 71. Kise imediately\ncalled the Sanborn police, asking\nthem to search the highway and\nthe Clements road, authorized a\nbroadcast over KNHD and left for\nthe scene, accompanied by Deputy\nHarry Beaty.\nThe Sanborn marshal could\nfind no trace of the car.\nAbout 10 minutes after the last\ntrain left the station, the operator\nsaid, there was a knock at the\ndoor of the office in which he was\non duty alone. He opened the\ndoor and a man entered.\nHolding a r.ickle plated gun in\nhis left hand, the bandit ordered\nSchultz to open the cash drawer\nin which there was about $1.25\nin silver and some pennies.\nNot satisfied he demanded that\n,the operator open the safe.\nSchultz did and handed him a\ntin box containing the day\u2019s re\nceipts of about $25.\n\u201cBring out the rest,\u201d the thug\nordered.\nMoney in Bag\nSchultz handed him the canvas\nbag, marked SI,OOO on the out\nside but containing twice that\namount.\nHitting him on the face with\nhis hand, the man left the depot.\nSchultz ran to the south win-\ndow and watched him cross the\ntracks, then lieard a ear start and\nsaw it moving north on the high\nway. It is believed that an ac\ncomplice was waiting in the ma\nchine.\nSheriff Kise\u2019s investigation was\ninterrupted by a business trip to\nthe Twin Cities Wednesday, but\nhe is working on several angles.\nSchultz described his assilant\nas about 30 years of age, five feet,\nten inches tall, between 160 and\n180 pounds in weight, with a dark\ncomplexion. He wore a greyish\ntweed overcoat, black hat and\nold rubbers.\nEFFORTS MADE TO\nFEED PHEASANTS\nBIRDS FAIRLY WELL\nCARED FOR, QUIST\nSAYS AFTER TRIP\nSeveral farmers in the com\nmunity have reported that pheas\nants are suffering a food shortage\nsince recent snows which blank\neted fields about a foot deep.\nGrant Adsit of near Belview\nsays that pheasants are coming\ninto his barnyard to feed, being\nunable to procure food in the\nfields.\nGame Warden W. H. Quist\nagrees that some birds are appar\nently in need of food. On a trip\nTuesday through Wabasso, Lucan,\nSanborn and Walnut Grove he\nsaw more pheasants on the roads\nthan ever before this winter.\n\u201cThe pheasants in this county\nare fairly well cared for, how\never,\u201d he says, reporting that 20\nfeed hoppers have been put out\nby the Redwood County Game\nprotective league. Morgan sports\nmen are paying farmers for grain\nused in feeding the birds and Lu\ncan residents are paying for feed\nand distributing grain.\nFarmers seeing flocks which ap\nparently need feed are asked to\ncontact Mr. Quist.\nSale Successful\nS. L. Park\u2019s sale of purebred\nHampshire gilts brought about\n125 bidders from Minnesota,\nNorth Dakota, lowa and Illinois\nto the Park farm in Redwood\nFalls township Tuesday. Mr.\nPark disposed of 37 sows from the\nfamous herd at an average price\nof $51.40 each.\nDr. and Mrs. L. J. Holm berg of\nCanby were here Sunday to visit\nMr. and Mrs. M. L Holmberg.\nTrophies, and Team That\u2019s After One\nThe seven trophies pictured\nabove, on display in Hillig Broth\ners window in Redwood Falls,\nwill be awarded declamatory and\nbasketball winners after March\ncompetition. Two sub-district\nMorton\u2019s basketball team, with\nonly one defeat against its rec\nord, is planning to make things\ntough for opponents in the sub\ndistrict meet here next week. The\nboys are: kneeling, left to right,\nRaymond Bucholz, William Matt\nHot Off Wire, Gazette Brings\nLatest Associated Press News\nHot off the wires!\nThe* Gazette brings today to\nRedwood Falls a t.ew civic asset\nand new prestige.\nWith this issue The Gazette be\ngins publication of the news dis\npatches of The Associated Press,\nand thereby takes its place among\nthe leading newspapers large\nand small of the nation which\nmake up the membership of this\ngreat, co-operative newsgathering\norganization.\nLinked with the gigantic 2&5,-\n000-mile network of The Associa\nted Press, The Gazette receives in\nits own offices, by telephone ser\nvice from AP\u2019s Minneapolis bur\neau, a running account of world\nevents as they are happening.\nThis paper is now one of the\nowners of the association which\nprovides its state, domestic and\nforeign dispatches. This and 1,400\nother member newspapers contrpl\nThe Associated Press and operate\nit, not for profit, but for the bene\nfit of their readers, who have a\nright to an impartial account of\nwhat is happening in the world.\nThe Associated Press cannot be\ninfluenced by political or other\nconsideration; it cannot transmit\none-sided or inaccurate news dis\npatches. It must stick to its job of\nfactual reporting. Its news is not\nfor sale to commercial interests,\ngovernment offices, or to any one,\nand it is the only press association\nin the world serving newspapers\nexclusively. The tremendous cost\nof gathering and distributing the\nnews of the world, which runs to\nmillions of dollars yearly, is\nborne by the members on a pro\nrata basis.\nIn the United States and Can\nada, 7,500 reporters and editors\nare on the job day and night,\nalert for any newsworthy happen\ning. There are 92 bureaus in the\nUnited States, strategically locat\ned to expedite the news.\nThe Associated Press also main\ntains bureaus and correspondents\nin 252 principal cities abroad, as\nsuring the readers of The Gazette\nof foreign news gathered factually\nand objectively for the consump\ntion of American readers.\nBesides the large staff of ex\nperienced Associated Press per\nsonnel, The Gazette is further\nprotected in its news coverage by\nthe fact that every one of the\nmember papers of the organiza\ntion must make its own news\navailable for the use of other\nmembers.\nThus, the daily work of thou\nsands of trained reporters and\neditors of The Associated Press\nstaff is supplemented by a veri\ntable army of expert news gather\ners throughout the nation.\nThe Gazette is proud to identify\nitself with The Associated Press,\nand to become a part of it It is a\nstep which means greater service\nto its readers than has been poss\nible in the past.\nShanghai\u2014 (/P) Japanese war\nplanes raided Chinese air dromes\non the southeast China coast to\nday in search for the base from\nwhich Shanghai yesterday bom\nbarded the Japanese islands of\nFormosa. On the widespread\nCentral China war front north\nwest of Nanking, Japanese col\numns rode toward the south\nagainst the Lunghai railway cor\nridor.\nwinners and the district champion\nand runner-up in basketball will\nreceive one and the winners in\noratory, dramatics and humorous\ndivisions of the district declama\ntory contest.\nke, Dale Bucholz, Captain Severin\nBidinger, Terry Hagen, Clifford\nDaby; back row, Kenneth Daby\u201e\nstudent manager; James Sallee,\nEarl Nerbum, Donald Sutten, Le\nland-Dermer and Loren R. Waugh,\ncoach.\nThe weather\u2014 (lP) \u2014Considerable\ncloudine* Jgnight and Friday, not\nso cold in west portions tonight,\nrising temperature Friday.\nWashington\u2014 (lP) \u2014Hungary re\nvived the whole question of war\ndebts today by announcing a pro\nposal for settling her obligations\nto the USA. She offered to pay\n\u201c100 cents on the dollar\u201d of her\noriginal indebtedness, minus in\nterest.\nLondon\u2014 (lP) \u2014Prime Minister\nChamberlain\u2019s \u201crealistic\u201d program\nfor bargaining with the Fascist\npowers for the peace of Europe\ntoday was reported advanced by\ncommon acceptance of the British\nplan for withdrawal of \u201cforeign\u201d\nvolunteers in the Spanish civil\nwar. Ur. Ernst Woermann, Ger\nman charge d\u2019 affairres, visited\nthe Earl of Plymouth. British\nunder secretary for foreign affairs\nand informed sources said he\nagreed to the British \u201cvolunteer\u201d\nproposal.\nPossible Appointee\nSt. Paul JP \u2014Julian E. Mor\nten, Redwood Falls attorney, to\nday was prominently mentioned\nabout the capital as a successor\nto William H. Lamson whose re\nsignation as secretary of three\nstate boards is reported to have\nbeen requested.\nLamson, secretary of the state\nboard of investments since the\nyear 1917 and to the executive\ncouncil and the pardon board\nsince 1925, is the last major Re\npublican appointee holding office\nin the Farmer-Labor administra\ntion.\nMorten is a prominent Farmer-\nLaborite in Redwood Falls who\nin the past four years has repre\nsented the state banking depart\nment as attorney in several cases\nin that section and for a time\nserved under Governor Benson\nwhen the latter was state bank\ning commissioner. Morten is a\npersonal friend of C. A. Halver\nson, state treasurer, and a member\nof the executive council.\nGovernor Benson and attorney\ngeneral William Ervin who with\nHalverson comprise the liberal\ncouncil majority were non-com\nmital when approached on the\nLamson issue today.\n2 High School\nTourneys Will\nBe Held Here\nAMATEURS WILL JOUST\nAT WALNUT GROVE\nSTARTING TONIGHT\nBasketball tournaments will\noccupy the limelight in Red\nwood county during the next\nthree weekends as 21 teams\nincluding nearly 200 players\ncompete before thousands of\nfans in three meets, arrang\ned to determine the county\namateur league champion,\ntwo high school sub-district\nwinners and the tenth dis\ntrict entrant in the regional\nmeet.\nRedwood Falls will be the\nscene of the two high school\nmeets March 3, 4 and 5 and\nMarch 11 and 12 and Walnut\nGrove is host to the amateur lea\ngue playoff tonight and Saturday.\nRedwood Falls will be repre\nsented at Walnut Grove by the\nModern Electric five which finish\ned its league season with one de\nfeat. The Electrics will meet\nLamberton and Belview, defend\ning champions, will battle Walnut\nGrove in the opening round to\nnight Belview finished its sea\nson with one defeat while Walnut\nGrove was beaten twice in league\nplay and Lamberton three times.\nThe Walnuts were the one team\nable to dump the powerful Elec\ntrics. Winners will meet in the\nfinals and losers in the consola\ntion game Saturday night.\nThe winning\u2019quint will receive\ntwo-fifths of the proceeds after\ndeducting SSO for expenses and\nthe remaining three teams each\none-fifth.\n11 In Sub-district\nThe sub-district meet will bring\n11 teams here from smaller high\nschools of the district to play nine\ngames in deciding the two en\ntrants from the group in the dis\ntrict meet the following week.\nGaylord and Walnut Grove, the\nlatter a darkhorse, carried off\nsub-district honors last year and\na repetition is possible since they\nare in opposite brackets. How\never the \u201cexperts\u201d look for Mor\nton and Gaylord to come through\nfor the honors, qualifying their\nTwo Games Left\nRedwood Falls cagers have\ntwo games left on their\nschedule before they enter\ndistrict play. Friday evening\nthey play at Hutchinson\nagainst the fast rangy team\nthey nosed out a month ago.\nTuesday night they meet\nSpringfield here. The field\ners defeated the Cardinals\nrecently at Springfield.\npredictions with the observation\nthat anything can happen in these\nmeets.\nGaylord was fortunate in the\ndrawing and will not be on the\nfloor the first night, its first op\nponent being the winner of the\nMorgan-Wabasso encounter which\nopens the tournament. Echo, one\nof the tough teams beaten by\nGaylord last year, likewise drew\na bye and will test the winner of\nthe first night Gibbon-Winthrop\ngame in the second encounter\nMarch 4. Survivors of the sec\nond night games will battle it out\nSaturday night.\nPick Redwood Foe\nIn the second bracket, Walnut\nGrove meets Delhi the first night\nwhile the powerful Morton quint,\nbeaten only once this season, will\nwait until the second evening to\nlaunch its campaign against the\nwinner. Franklin and Belview\nalso drew byes arid will get their\ntaste of tourney fire in their game\ncompleting the four game slate\nFriday evening. Franklin upset\nthe favored Morton quint by one\npoint after an off and on season\nlast year and it will be a tourney\nfeature if the teams come together\nin the tourney again this season.\nRedwood Falls High players\nwill watch the sub-district with\nmore than usual interest since\ntheir first district opponent the\nfollowing week will be in doubt\nuntil the winner of the first\nbracket is decided. The winner of\nthe B bracket will be Spring\nfield\u2019s first foe in the district\nmeet.\nLamberton and Sleepy Eye are\nscheduled to open that session of\nbasketball March 10 at 6:30 p. m.\nafter which Fairfax will cope\nwith.the New Ulm quint, defend\ning champion and a pre-meet\nfavorite. The acme in crowd-pull\ning power would be realized if\nMorton and Redwood should meet\non the second evening March 11,\na situation which would neces\nsitate Morton\u2019s winning three\nprevious encounters and Redwood\none.\nR. W. WHYTE HURT\nR. W. Whyte, high school custo\ndian, is in bed suffering with\ntorn ligaments of the knee sus\ntained when he stepped onto a\nchair Wednesday morning.","height":"25521","width":"20385"}}
